@startuml KTM_Problems_Constraints
!theme plain
skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam noteBackgroundColor #FFE8E8
skinparam noteBorderColor #CC0000
skinparam noteFontColor #000000
skinparam rectangle {
    BackgroundColor #F0F0F0
    BorderColor #333333
    FontColor #000000
}

title Keyboard Transparency Monitor - Architectural Problems & Solutions\n\n

rectangle "CRITICAL DETECTION CHALLENGES" {
    note right
        **PROBLEM 1: Input Device Access Detection**
        Current: Cannot directly detect keyboard access
        Reason: Windows API limitations without kernel driver
        
        Attempted Solutions:
        • WMIC process inspection (deprecated API)
        • Handle.exe analysis (requires Sysinternals)
        • ETW tracing (complex, poorly documented)
        
        Root Cause:
        Windows deliberately restricts input device access
        to unprivileged user-mode processes for security
        
        **Impact:** Real-time keyboard monitoring limited
        to heuristic analysis (process names, paths)
        
        **Solution:** Kernel-mode driver required
        (like commercial antivirus software)
    end note

    note right
        **PROBLEM 2: Threading & Qt Signal Issues**
        Current: Callbacks from background thread to UI
        Reason: PySide6 requires UI updates from main thread only
        
        Attempted Solutions:
        • Direct callback passing → crashes (race condition)
        • Qt Signals → works but overhead
        • Thread-safe queue → not implemented
        
        Root Cause:
        MonitorService runs in background thread,
        but PySide6 widgets must be updated from main thread
        
        **Impact:** Missed updates, potential crashes
        
        **Solution:** Implemented Qt Signals pattern
        (thread-safe event dispatch to main loop)
    end note

    note right
        **PROBLEM 3: WMIC Deprecation**
        Current: WMIC not available on Windows 11+
        Reason: Microsoft deprecated WMI Command-Line
        
        Attempted Solutions:
        • PowerShell Get-Process (slower)
        • WMI COM objects (complex, verbose)
        • psutil only (limited handle info)
        
        Root Cause:
        No standardized process inspection API on modern Windows
        Microsoft phasing out old WMI CLI tools
        
        **Impact:** Cannot reliably get handle counts
        Performance degradation on newer Windows
        
        **Solution:** Switch to PowerShell WMI or
        implement Windows Driver Kit solution
    end note
}

rectangle " ARCHITECTURAL CONSTRAINTS" {
    note right
        **CONSTRAINT 1: Privilege Escalation**
        Issue: Many detections require administrator rights
        
        Required for:
        • Process handle inspection
        • Digital signature validation
        • Registry access (System hive)
        • File system deep inspection
        
        Current Status: Not implemented
        Workaround: Run as Administrator (manual user action)
        
        **Impact:** Limited detection without admin privileges
    end note

    note right
        **CONSTRAINT 2: Performance**
        Issue: Scanning 300+ processes takes significant time
        
        Bottlenecks:
        • WMIC queries (2-3 sec per scan)
        • Risk analysis per-process (overhead)
        • Database writes (I/O bound, SQLite locking)
        • Network I/O for signature validation
        
        Current: 5 sec scan interval
        Needed: 1 sec for true real-time response
        
        **Solution:** Incremental scanning, async queries,
        caching, connection pooling (not implemented)
    end note

    note right
        **CONSTRAINT 3: Cross-Platform Complexity**
        Issue: Different OS = different APIs and limitations
        
        Windows:
        • WMIC/PowerShell/WMI (deprecated)
        • Registry inspection (complex)
        • Digital signatures (code signing)
        
        Linux:
        • /proc filesystem parsing (simple)
        • /sys inspection (kernel info)
        • strace/ptrace (limited, slow)
        
        macOS:
        • lsof analysis (file handles)
        • IOKit inspection (hardware)
        • Sandbox restrictions (App Store)
        
        Current: Only Windows partially implemented
        **Impact:** Code bloat, maintenance overhead
    end note
}

rectangle "DATA FLOW PROBLEMS" {
    note right
        **PROBLEM 4: Callback Registration Timing**
        Issue: Callbacks registered AFTER monitor starts
        
        Timeline Bug:
        1. MonitorService.start() ← scan begins IMMEDIATELY
        2. register_callback() ← UI subscribes NOW
        3. process_detected() ← but first scan already done!
        
        Result: First scan missed by UI, no processes visible
        
        **Status:** FIXED - Reversed init order
        (callbacks now registered BEFORE start())
    end note

    note right
        **PROBLEM 5: Database Contention**
        Issue: Background thread writes to SQLite
        SQLite limitation: Single-threaded by default
        
        Result: Lock contention, slow queries
        Frequent: "database is locked" errors
        
        Current Workaround: WAL mode enabled (partial)
        Better Solution: Connection pooling (not implemented)
        
        **Impact:** Occasional database access delays
    end note
}

rectangle "DETECTION ACCURACY ISSUES" {
    note right
        **PROBLEM 6: High False Positive Rate**
        Current detections too simplistic:
        
        • Process names: "keylog" → too specific
        • Paths: "%TEMP%" → many legitimate apps use it
        • Handle count: >500 → many system procs hit this
        • Unsigned: Many Windows apps are unsigned
        
        Result: Most system processes = low risk
        True threats: Indistinguishable from noise
        
        Better Approach:
        • Behavioral analysis (relaunch patterns)
        • Network anomalies (C&C communication)
        • System call tracing (very slow)
        • ML classification (requires training data)
        
        **Impact:** Cannot reliably detect advanced threats
    end note

    note right
        **PROBLEM 7: Evasion Techniques Not Detected**
        Current detection scope is limited:
        
        NOT detected:
        • Process spoofing (fake name like svchost.exe)
        • DLL injection (loaded from parent process)
        • Registry injection (runs before detection)
        • Kernel mode rootkits (below userspace)
        • Code caves (code injection into existing proc)
        • Privilege escalation exploits
        
        Requires:
        • Kernel driver (highest privilege level)
        • Real-time system call hooking
        • Memory scanning & analysis
        • Behavior prediction ML model
        
        **Impact:** Advanced threats may bypass detection
    end note
}

@enduml
